>> title: Brinner: Pancakes, Eggs & Sheet-Pan Bacon
>> cuisine: American
>> tags: breakfast, kid-friendly, teaching
>> servings: 2

-- Breakfast school. The lesson is SEQUENCE: the oven cooks the bacon
-- unattended, the batter rests while it does, and the eggs go last because
-- they wait for no one. Three kinds of heat control in one meal.

Lay @bacon{8%slices} on a foil-lined #sheet pan{} in a single layer. Put it in a COLD oven, then set the oven to 400F. Set a #timer{} for 15 minutes - sheet-pan bacon needs no flipping and no splatter. Check at 15; pull when it's your kind of crispy (usually 17-20 minutes). Drain on paper towels.

While the bacon works, make the batter: empty one batch of @../components/breakfast/pancake-dry-mix{1.75%cups} into a #bowl{}. In a second bowl, whisk @buttermilk{1 1/4%cups}, @egg{1}, and @butter{2%tbsp}(melted). Pour wet into dry and stir until JUST combined - lumps are fine. Overmixing makes tough pancakes. Let the batter rest 10 minutes; this is when it thickens and gets fluffy.

Heat a #griddle{} or big #skillet{} over medium. Grease lightly with @butter{1%tsp}. Pour 1/4-cup pancakes. Flip when the top is covered in popped bubbles and the edges look set (about 2-3 minutes) - one flip only. Another 1-2 minutes on side two. Hold finished pancakes in the turned-off (still warm) oven with the bacon.

Eggs last: crack @eggs{4} into a bowl with @kosher salt{1/4%tsp} and beat well. Melt @butter{1%tbsp} in a nonstick #skillet{} over LOW heat. Add eggs and push them around slowly with a spatula. Pull the pan OFF the heat while they still look slightly wet and glossy - they finish cooking on the plate.

Serve everything together with @maple syrup{1/4%cup} and the bacon.

-- Round 2 (Thursday): same recipe, Owen runs the whole sequence himself.
